</note>
<note id="fs-id1167835307262" class="try">
<exercise id="fs-id1167835337502">
<problem id="fs-id1167826782246">
<para id="fs-id1167834061875">Identify the slope and <emphasis effect="italics">y</emphasis>-intercept from the equation of the line.</para>
<para id="fs-id1167835358594"><span class="token">ⓐ</span> <m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mn>4</m:mn><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:mfrac><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:math> <span class="token">ⓑ</span> <m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>12</m:mn></m:mrow></m:math></para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1167834058851">
<para id="fs-id1167831103053"><span class="token">ⓐ</span> <m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mn>4</m:mn><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:mfrac><m:mo>;</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mn>0</m:mn><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math><newline/><span class="token">ⓑ</span> <m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mfrac><m:mo>;</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mn>0</m:mn><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mn>6</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math></para>
</solution>
</exercise>
</note>
<para id="fs-id1167835324473">We have graphed a line using the slope and a point. Now that we know how to find the slope and <emphasis effect="italics">y</emphasis>-intercept of a line from its equation, we can use the <emphasis effect="italics">y</emphasis>-intercept as the point, and then count out the slope from there.</para>
<example id="fs-id1167835356745">
<exercise id="fs-id1167831923635">
